$$ \rm{Emissions}=\left[N\times \frac{Y}{N}\right]\times \left[\frac{E}{Y}\times \frac{C}{E}\right]=Y\times \frac{C}{Y}=\rm{GDP}\times \rm{Technology,}$$
\end{document}
where technology (C/Y) is simply the ratio of CO2 emissions to GDP. In 2006, 29.12 Gt CO2 were emitted globally while global GDP amounted to $47.267 trillion, so that the technology or emissions to GDP ratio was 0.62 tCO2 per $1000 GDP. From 1980 to 2006, the world’s C/Y ratio fell from 0.92 to 0.62 tCO2 per $1,000 GDP. This is seen in Fig. 7.7 where the emissions intensities of selected countries are also provided. In making these calculations, a measure of purchasing power parity (PPP) GDP is used.
